  "prompt": "Why does the sun rise in the east and set in the west but not the north and south?",
  "response": "The reason the sun rises in the east and sets in the west has to do with the rotation of the Earth on its axis. The Earth rotates from west to east, which means that as it spins, different parts of the planet move into and out of sunlight.\n\nHere\u2019s a more detailed explanation:\n\n1. **Earth's Rotation**: The Earth rotates around its axis, which is an imaginary line that runs from the North Pole to the South Pole. This rotation occurs in a counterclockwise direction when viewed from above the North Pole.\n\n2. **Apparent Movement of the Sun**: Because of this rotation, as the Earth spins, the sun appears to move across the sky. In the morning, as your location on Earth rotates into the sunlight, you see the sun appear on the eastern horizon. As the day progresses, the Earth continues to rotate, moving your location westward relative to the sun, making it appear to rise higher in the sky.\n\n3. **Setting in the West**: In the evening, as your location continues to rotate away from the sun, it dips below the western horizon, making it appear to set in the west.\n\n4. **The Equator's Influence**: Depending on your latitude, the angle at which the sun rises and sets can vary. Near the equator, the sun rises nearly vertically and sets directly opposite. At higher latitudes, such as in mid-latitude regions, the sun follows a longer arc across the sky, and its path may change with the seasons, affecting how far north or south it appears to rise or set.\n\nThe sun does not rise or set in the north or south primarily because of the Earth's axial tilt and the consistent direction of its rotation. Only during the equinoxes will the sun rise exactly in the east and set exactly in the west for all observers on Earth; at other times of the year, its rising and setting points will vary along the horizon, but they will remain within the eastern and western quadrants.",
